Theory:
In Java, constructor overloading allows a class to have multiple constructors with different parameter lists. This provides flexibility in object creation by initializing objects in different ways depending on the data provided. Constructors are special methods that are automatically invoked when an object is created. They have the same name as the class and do not have a return type. 

In this program, the Student class demonstrates constructor overloading by 
providing four constructors: 
1. Default constructor (no arguments). 
2. Constructor with roll number only. 
3. Constructor with roll number and name. 
4. Constructor with roll number, name, and department. 

This allows objects to be created with varying levels of initialization.
*/

// Student class definition
class Student {
    int rollNumber;
    String name;
    String department;
    
    // Default constructor - assigns default values
    Student() {
        rollNumber = 0;
        name = "Not Assigned";
        department = "Not Assigned";
    }
    
    // Constructor with roll number only
    Student(int rollNumber) {
        this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
        this.name = "Not Assigned";
        this.department = "Not Assigned";
    }
    
    // Constructor with roll number and name
    Student(int rollNumber, String name) {
        this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
        this.name = name;
        this.department = "Not Assigned";
    }
    
    // Constructor with all parameters
    Student(int rollNumber, String name, String department) {
        this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
        this.name = name;
        this.department = department;
    }
    
    // Method to display student details
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Roll: " + rollNumber + ", Name: " + name + ", Dept: " + department);
    }
}

// Main class to test constructor overloading
public class Exp4b {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating objects using different constructors
        Student s1 = new Student();                                 // Default constructor
        Student s2 = new Student(101);                              // Roll number only
        Student s3 = new Student(102, "JISHAN");                    // Roll number and name
        Student s4 = new Student(103, "NINJAL", "CSE");             // Roll, name, department
        Student s5 = new Student(104, "AARAV", "IT");               // Full details
        Student s6 = new Student(105, "SANA", "AIML");              // Full details
        Student s7 = new Student(106, "OMKAR", "ECE");              // Full details
        Student s8 = new Student(107, "FATIMA", "Mechanical");      // Full details
        
        // Displaying student information
        s1.display();
        s2.display();
        s3.display();
        s4.display();
        s5.display();
        s6.display();
        s7.display();
        s8.display();
    }
}
